[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering security manager setup**\n\nThe JDK21 security manager gets deprecated, but it’s possible to enable it with a specific flag when building. I realize if PureJavaReflectionProvider$Reflections is initialized, I can’t reset it; we might need a completely separate test. However, I wonder if we can handle both branches of logic in one JVM? It seems tricky. By forcing a fallback to avoid a newInstance call, I could cover some lines, but I still might miss others. I’ll need to think this through further!\n\n**Exploring test execution strategy**\n\nI’m considering adding a fallback test in the same class, but I wonder if that’s even possible since Reflections can only be initialized once in the same JVM. Maybe forking per test class could work, but likely Gradle runs tests in a single JVM, and the order of tests isn't guaranteed. I could use JUnit’s @Order annotation, but static state complicates things. To ensure proper coverage for the fallback, it looks like I'd need a separate test with different class loading!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_012fd70a5b8910ed0169fbecf904a8819599b96e9473138f79\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp--0CqCP7uPGNGr8JIiMlqOr0BFZD5hq1waDPXYl5fW6sWI-Wo_589RM5vOAm-o6NDcQ71AHzbD8tiTM4kw5GGxWGU5TdMjfTooOGKpWsKGkw5iy3jnxUeQHnxmPyJVlNoInuYBBrgUYBZt4EPYpAlLIhewh76tNfdp6a989MaYQrlHea7SQdIA1PMuzM9cC2_B5GHbOWGmYRoZ7BaQzScQgjpx5kmqODhuD9EUYsu3QkanviTBf_dJOC0arsByGQfARSRuvCLG1V7dyto6GSowLosMxiAjb__9PfDoNvmOSsWMKoGGGtwra4DsuMGvQlkGygGoB4kG_3nPQWGy88uB6ev3Z5oJL1n8Q5M9PIxigPvbR2fvLciUVENOy8p1BH9ere_vsnBGISw8XCagP0O3jVBHJGPDld9svrun-cuA2E-Drvl1nV_aff3yD5z1l4rmmBnhwYHmSeJ5rwzcI4fUyb3Q4-rHpBq4Qkp-dSgCnFWszquGLNWNrd1vRRUDr2cZFEWfLlwI-1fLU674MgtOU-1cu4D0TPdbGdSryYUfD5dcVqw17MuJYp9fdjZJcXLUqF4bAnOAJgLYlpwhU8nqYtYyjcX61-geTZAgKMJtuBCxk2vbQXPC2gu4pRmd7lgPvunbKgh4QOIIe8RRBdfMeSmbejVuzjXkUtmu0d2xYhgMdm3aS46n4Zmm8M9qviMyBsjfM